{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The wait time between retries doubles with each consecutive failure, up to a configured maximum.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is primarily backoff math/state progression at a local function/object boundary. The core failure is incorrect exponential growth or cap logic, which does not require module wiring or I/O to reproduce.","test_description":"Test the backoff calculator with consecutive failure counts (e.g., 1..N) and assert delays follow 2^n progression until `maxBackoffMs`, then stay capped.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.84,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The retry logic correctly identifies a rate-limit response and computes the appropriate wait time before the next attempt.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is the handoff between response parsing/classification and retry scheduling. A unit test of either piece alone can miss mismatches (e.g., status/header mapping not consumed correctly by scheduler).","test_description":"Wire retry orchestrator + response classifier + backoff policy. Feed synthetic HTTP responses (e.g., 429 with/without retry headers) through the same interface used by `call()`, and assert whether retry is triggered and what delay is scheduled.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.71,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"After the wait, the client actually resends the original request and returns the successful result to the caller transparently.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This depends on interaction between timer/backoff scheduling, request replay, and result propagation. Mocking too low (single function) can miss that the original request payload/context is not preserved across retry.","test_description":"Use retry client with a controllable clock and stub transport: first attempt returns rate-limit, second succeeds. Advance clock by scheduled delay and assert transport received the same original request on retry and `call()` resolves with successful payload.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.09,"Integration":0.84,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"After the configured maximum number of retries, the client returns a typed `QuotaExhaustedError` rather than a generic error.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The behavior spans retry counter exhaustion plus error translation at the public API boundary. Unit-testing only the error class or only the counter can miss incorrect wiring that leaks generic exceptions.","test_description":"Configure low `maxRetries`, force repeated rate-limit responses via stub transport, run `call()`, and assert rejection is specifically `QuotaExhaustedError` with expected typed fields.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.73,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full retry chain — initial call, backoff retries, quota tracking — terminates correctly and does not loop indefinitely before surfacing the error.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is an end-to-end control-flow safety property across several local modules (retry loop, backoff, quota state). The real failure appears in composition (e.g., counter not incremented, terminal condition never reached).","test_description":"Run the full retry pipeline with deterministic clock and always-rate-limited responses. Assert bounded number of attempts equals configured limit and final failure is surfaced within deterministic virtual time; include a hard test timeout to catch non-termination.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.86,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Requests issued concurrently from multiple async callers in the same process all draw from the same shared quota bucket.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is fundamentally a cross-module shared-state/concurrency behavior. Unit tests on isolated functions cannot validate contention and shared bucket accounting across concurrent `call()` invocations.","test_description":"Instantiate one client/shared quota manager, launch multiple concurrent `call()` promises, and use a deterministic stub transport plus instrumentation to verify aggregate token usage comes from one shared bucket and throttling affects callers globally.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.9,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When multiple requests are waiting to be sent, they are dispatched in the order they were originally submitted.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"FIFO dispatch is a queueing/scheduler contract that emerges when request queue + dispatcher + quota gate interact. Single-function tests can miss reordering introduced by async coordination.","test_description":"Queue several requests quickly under constrained quota so they must wait, then release capacity stepwise and assert dispatch order matches submission order using captured send timestamps/sequence numbers.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.88,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
